03686nmm a2200577Ia 9780801471254DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014712547 a10.7591/97808014712542doi  a(DE-B1597)481679  a(OCoLC)984688331  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBT102b.A46 199104a248.2/011 aAlston, William P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerceiving God :bThe Epistemology of Religious Experience /cWilliam P. Alston. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Perceiving God, William P. Alston offers a clear and provocative account of the epistemology of religious experience. He argues that the "perception of God"—his term for direct experiential awareness of God—makes a major contribution to the grounds of religious belief. Surveying the variety of reported direct experiences of God among laypersons and famous mystics, Alston demonstrates that a person can be justified in holding certain beliefs about God on the basis of mystical experience. Through the perception that God is sustaining one in being, for example, one can justifiably believe that God is indeed sustaining one in being.Alston offers a detailed discussion of our grounds for taking sense perception and other sources of belief—including introspection, memory, and mystical experience—to be reliable and to confer justification. He then uses this epistemic framework to explain how our perceptual beliefs about God can be justified. Alston carefully addresses objections to his chief claims, including problems posed by non-Christian religious traditions. He also examines the way in which mystical perception fits into the larger picture of grounds for religious belief.Suggesting that religious experience, rather than being a purely subjective phenomenon, has real cognitive value, Perceiving God will spark intense debate and will be indispensable reading for those interested in philosophy of religion, epistemology, and philosophy of mind, as well as for theologians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aExperience (Religion). 0aGod (Christianity)xKnowableness. 0aGodxKnowableness. 0aKnowledge, Theory of (Religion). 4aPhilosophy. 4aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147125440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801471254423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801471254/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles